title: Abstract Art
description: Art with a degree of independence from visual references in the world

title: Abstract Expressionism
description: American post–World War II art movement

title: Academicism
description: Style of painting and sculpture produced under the influence of European academies of art

title: Action painting
description: style of painting in which paint is spontaneously dribbled, splashed or smeared onto the canvas

title: American Realism
description: American art movement

title: Art Brut
description: Art created outside the boundaries of official culture by those untrained in the arts

title: Art Deco
description: Influential visual arts design style which first appeared in France during the 1920s

title: Art Nouveau (Modern)
description: Style of art and architecture about 1890 to 1911

title: Automatic Painting
description: Method of art-making in which the artist suppresses conscious control over the making process

title: Baroque
description: Cultural movement, starting around 1600

title: Biedermeier
description: A Center Eurpoe movement in which arts appealed to common sensibilities

title: Byzantine
description: Art of the Byzantine (Eastern Roman) Empire

title: Classicism
description: An aesthetic attitude dependent on principles based in the culture, art and literature of ancient Greece and Rome

title: Color Field Painting
description: A style of abstract painting that emerged in New York City during the 1940s and 1950s

title: Conceptual Art
description: Art in which the concept(s) or idea(s) involved in the work take precedence over traditional aesthetic, technical, and material concerns

title: Constructivism
description: Constructivism was an artistic and architectural philosophy that originated in Russia beginning in 1913 by Vladimir Tatlin.

title: Contemporary Realism
description: The contemporary realism movement is a North American style of painting which came into existence c. 1960s and early 1970s.

title: Costumbrismo
description: Costumbrismo is the pictorial interpretation of local everyday life, primarily in the Hispanic scene.

title: Cubism
description: Cubism is an early-20th-century avant-garde art movement.

title: Cubo-Expressionism
description: Cubo-Expressionism was an avant-garde art movement of Czech proponents of Cubism.

title: Cubo-Futurism
description: Cubo-Futurism was the main school of painting and sculpture practiced by Russian Futurists.

title: Cyber Art
description: Cyber art refers to the class of art produced with the help of computer software and hardware, often with an interactive or multimedia aspect.

title: Dada
description: An art movement of the European avant-garde in the early 20th century.

title: Divisionism
description: style in Neo-Impressionist painting, using the separation of colors into individual dots or patches which interact optically.

title: Environmental (Land) Art
description: Form of art creation in which landscape and the work of art are inextricably linked.

title: Expressionism
description: A modernist movement, initially in poetry and painting, originating in Germany at the beginning of the 20th century.

title: Fantastic Realism
description: The Vienna School of Fantastic Realism is a group of artists founded in Vienna in 1946.

title: Fauvism
description: Artistic style that emphasized painterly qualities and strong color over the representational or realistic values retained by Impressionism.

title: Feminist Art
description: Art that reflects women’s lives and experiences.

title: Fiber art
description: Artworks made of fiber and other textile materials, emphasizing aesthetic value over utility.

title: Futurism
description: An artistic and social movement that originated in Italy in the early 20th century.

title: Gongbi
description: Gongbi is a careful realist technique in Chinese painting.

title: Gothic
description: Style of Medieval art developed in Northern France

title: Graffiti Art
description: Graffiti is writing or drawings made on a wall or other surface.

title: Hard Edge Painting
description: Hard-edge painting is painting in which abrupt transitions are found between color areas.

title: High Renaissance
description: In art history, the High Renaissance is a short period of the most exceptional artistic production in the Italian states.

title: Hyper-Mannerism (Anachronism)
description: An anachronism is a chronological inconsistency in some arrangement.

title: Hyper-Realism
description: Hyperrealism is a genre of painting and sculpture resembling a high-resolution photograph.

title: Impressionism
description: A 19th-century art movement characterized by relatively small, thin, yet visible brush strokes.

title: Ink and wash painting
description: Ink wash painting, or sumi-e, is a type of East Asian brush painting that uses black ink in different concentrations.

title: International Gothic
description: A period of Gothic art which began in Burgundy, France, and northern Italy.

title: Intimism
description: Art movement of paintings and drawings of quiet domestic scenes

title: Japonism
description: European imitation of Japanese art during the 19th and 20th centuries

title: Junk Art
description: Art created from undisguised, but often modified, objects or products that are not normally considered art

title: Kinetic Art
description: Art genre of artworks that contains movement.

title: Kitsch
description: Art or other objects that appeal to popular rather than high art tastes

title: Lettrism
description: French avant-garde movement founded by Isadore Isou in mid-1940s Paris.

title: Light and Space
description: A loosely affiliated art movement related to op art, minimalism and geometric abstraction.

title: Lowbrow Art
description: Visual art movement that arose in the Los Angeles, California, area in the late 1970s.

title: Luminism
description: American landscape painting style of the 1850s – 1870s.

title: Lyrical Abstraction
description: Lyrical abstraction is either of two related but distinct trends in Post-war Modernist painting.

title: Magic Realism
description: A style of fiction that paints a realistic view of the modern world while also adding magical elements.

title: Mail Art
description: A populist artistic movement centered on sending small scale works through the postal service.

title: Mannerism (Late Renaissance)
description: A style in European art that emerged in the later years of the Italian High Renaissance

title: Maximalism
description: In the arts, maximalism, a reaction against minimalism, is an aesthetic of excess and redundancy.

title: Metaphysical art
description: A style of painting developed by the Italian artists Giorgio de Chirico and Carlo Carrà.

title: Minimalism
description: An art movement that began in post–World War II Western art in the 1960s and early 1970s

title: Modernismo
description: A Spanish-American literary and art movement

title: Mughal
description: A particular style of South Asian painting confined to miniatures.

title: Muralism
description: Piece of artwork painted or applied directly on a large permanent surface.

title: Naïve Art (Primitivism)
description: Visual art that is created by a person who lacks the formal education and training.

title: Nanga (Bunjinga)
description: A school of Japanese painting which flourished in the late Edo period.

title: Nas-Taliq
description: The predominant style in Persian calligraphy.

title: Neoclassicism
description: Western art movements that draw inspiration from the "classical" art and culture of Ancient Greece or Ancient Rome.

title: Neo-Concretism
description: A Brazilian art movement that splintered off from the larger Concrete Art movement.

title: Neo-Dada
description: A movement with audio, visual and literary manifestations that had similarities in method with earlier Dada artwork.

title: Neo-Expressionism
description: A style of late modernist or early-postmodern painting and sculpture that emerged in the late 1970s.

title: Neo-Figurative Art
description: An expressionist revival in modern form of figurative art.

title: Neo-Geo
description: An art movement that utilizes geometric abstraction and criticizes the industrialism and consumerism of modern society.

title: Neo-Minimalism
description: An amorphous art movement of the late 20th and early 21st centuries.

title: Neo-Pop Art
description: A postmodern art movement of the 1980s.

title: Neo-Rococo
description: The Neo-Rococo or Rococo Revival style emerged in Second Empire France.

title: New European Painting
description: Emerged in the 1980s and reached a critical point of major distinction in the 1990s.

title: Nihonga
description: Paintings made in accordance with traditional Japanese artistic conventions.

title: Northern Renaissance
description: Renaissance that occurred in the European countries north of the Alps.

title: Nouveau Réalisme
description: An artistic movement founded in 1960 by the art critic Pierre Restany and the painter Yves Klein.

title: Op Art
description: A style of visual art that uses optical illusions.

title: Orientalism
description: Imitation or depiction of Eastern culture.

title: Orphism
description: An offshoot of Cubism that focused on pure abstraction and bright colors.

title: Outsider art
description: Art created outside the boundaries of official culture by those untrained in the arts.

title: P&D (Pattern and Decoration)
description: A United States art movement from the mid-1970s to the early 1980s.

title: Photorealism
description: A genre of art where an artist attempts to produce an image as realistically as possible.

title: Pictorialism
description: A style in which the photographer has somehow manipulated what would otherwise be a straightforward photograph.

title: Pointillism
description: A technique of painting with small, distinct dots.

title: Pop Art
description: Fine art including imagery from popular and mass culture.

title: Post-Impressionism
description: Predominantly French art movement that developed roughly between 1886 and 1905.

title: Post-Minimalism
description: Art movement influenced by, or attempts to go beyond, the aesthetic of minimalism

title: Post-Painterly Abstraction
description: A term created by art critic Clement Greenberg as the title for an exhibit he curated.

title: Purism
description: A french movement that took place between 1918 and 1925.

title: Rayonism
description: A style of abstract art that developed in Russia in 1911

title: Realism
description: Artistic style of representing subjects realistically.

title: Regionalism
description: An American realist modern art movement that included paintings, murals and lithographs.

title: Renaissance
description: Painting, sculpture and decorative arts of that period of European history known as the Renaissance.

title: Rococo
description: 18th-century artistic movement and style.

title: Romanesque
description: Artistic style of Europe from approximately 1000 AD to the 13th century.

title: Romanticism
description: Period of artistic, literary, and intellectual movement that started in 18th century Europe.

title: Safavid Period
description: Art of the Persian Safavid dynasty from 1501 to 1722.

title: Shin-hanga
description: An art movement in early 20th-century Japan, during the Taishō and Shōwa periods.

title: Social Realism
description: International art movement flourishing in the interwar period. Reacts to the hardships suffered by people after the Great Crash.

title: Socialist Realism
description: A style of idealized realistic art that was developed in the Soviet Union.

title: Sōsaku hanga
description: An art movement in early 20th-century Japan.

title: Spatialism
description: An art movement founded by Italian artist Lucio Fontana in Milan in 1947.

title: Street art
description: Art that is public and temporary in public spaces.

title: Stuckism
description: Art movement founded in 1999 by Billy Childish and Charles Thomson.

title: Suprematism
description: An art movement focused on basic geometric forms, such as circles, squares, lines, and rectangles.

title: Symbolism
description: A late nineteenth-century art movement of French, Russian and Belgian origin.

title: Synchromism
description: An art movement founded in 1912 by American artists Stanton MacDonald-Wright and Morgan Russell.

title: Synthetism
description: A term used by post-Impressionist artists like Paul Gauguin, Émile Bernard and Louis Anquetin.

title: Tachisme
description: A French style of abstract painting popular in the 1940s and 1950s.

title: Tenebrism
description: A style of painting using profoundly pronounced chiaroscuro, where there are violent contrasts of light and dark.

title: Timurid Period
description: A style of art originating during the rule of the Timurid Empire (1370-1507).

title: Tonalism
description: An artistic style that emerged in the 1880s. Landscape paintings with an overall tone of colored atmosphere or mist.

title: Transavantgarde
description: An art movement that swept through Italy, and the rest of Western Europe, in the late 1970s and 1980s.

title: Ukiyo-e
description: A genre of Japanese art which flourished from the 17th through 19th centuries.

title: Verism
description: The artistic preference of contemporary everyday subject matter instead of the heroic or legendary.

title: Yamato-e
description: A style of Japanese painting of the late Heian period and inspired by Tang dynasty paintings

title: Figurative Expressionism
description: A 20th-century visual art style or movement that first took hold in Boston.

title: Street Photography
description: Photography conducted for art or enquiry that features random incidents within public places.

title: Mozarabic
description: Refers to art of Mozarabs, Iberian Christians living in Al-Andalus.

title: Digital Art
description: Collective term for art that is generated digitally with the computer

title: Sumi-e (Suiboku-ga)
description: A type of East Asian brush painting that uses black ink in different concentrations.

title: Fantasy Art
description: A type of art that explores fantasy and imagination.

title: Contemporary
description: Art of the present time beginning with Pop Art and Conceptual Art.

title: Hellenistic
description: The art of the Hellenistic period generally taken to begin with the death of Alexander the Great.

title: Early Byzantine (c. 330–750)
description: Art of the Early Byzantine (Eastern Roman) Empire

title: Middle Byzantine (c. 850–1204)
description: Art of the Middle Byzantine (Eastern Roman) Empire

title: Late Byzantine/Palaeologan Renaissance (c. 1261–1453)
description: Art of the Late Byzantine or Palaeologan (Eastern Roman) Empire

title: Macedonian Renaissance (867–1056)
description: Byzantine empire cultural movement during the reign of the Macedonian dynasty.

title: Precisionism
description: The first indigenous modern art movement in the United States.

title: Transautomatism
description: A modern style of painting founded by Friedensreich Hundertwasser.
